  <h1 class="title-2">1989 - The World Wide Web</h1>

  <div class="container">
    <p>
      In 1989, a groundbreaking idea was proposed by British computer scientist
      Tim Berners-Lee at CERN (the European Organization for Nuclear Research).
      This idea would eventually become the World Wide Web (WWW), a system that
      transformed the internet from a network used by researchers into a global
      space accessible to billions. With the World Wide Web, Tim Berners-Lee
      revolutionized how information was shared and accessed, creating the
      foundation for the internet we use today.
    </p>

    <p>
      In a time when the internet was primarily used by researchers for
      exchanging data and messages, Berners-Lee proposed a way to enable a more
      dynamic, interconnected world. His system would allow people to access
      information, navigate between documents using hyperlinks, and easily share
      content across a global network. The introduction of the World Wide Web
      marked a moment that would fundamentally change how humans interact with
      the digital world.
    </p>

    <h2>What is the World Wide Web?</h2>

    <p>
      The World Wide Web is a system for accessing and sharing information
      across the internet using hyperlinks. Berners-Leeâ€™s vision was to create a
      global information space where documents could be linked together,
      allowing users to navigate from one document to another simply by clicking
      on hyperlinks. This idea of interconnected documents laid the groundwork
      for the development of web browsers, web pages, and the expansive digital
      ecosystem that would follow.
    </p>
    <p>
      Before the World Wide Web, the internet existed mainly as a tool for
      scientific and academic communication. The Web made this information
      accessible to the general public, offering an easy-to-navigate platform
      that allowed individuals to discover and share information. It was a
      breakthrough in how we engage with data, offering a simple yet powerful
      means of accessing information online.
    </p>

    <h2>The Key Technologies Behind the Web</h2>

    <p>
      To bring the World Wide Web to life, Berners-Lee developed several key
      technologies:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <b>HTML (Hypertext Markup Language)</b>: A coding language used to
        create and format web pages, which would display text, images, and
        multimedia content.
      </li>
      <li>
        <b>HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol)</b>: A protocol that governs how
        web browsers and web servers communicate with each other to deliver
        content.
      </li>
      <li>
        <b>Web Browsers</b>: Software tools that allow users to view and
        interact with web pages. These browsers would become the primary
        interface through which people navigated the Web.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      In addition to developing these technologies, Berners-Lee created the
      first web browser, called WorldWideWeb, and developed the first website,
      hosted on a server at CERN, which explained how the Web worked and how
      others could use it. This set the stage for the Web to expand, bringing
      the internet to millions of people worldwide.
    </p>

