    <h2>The First Website</h2>
    <p>
      In 1991, Berners-Lee launched the first-ever website at CERN:
      info.cern.ch. This website was a simple, text-based page that explained
      the basics of the World Wide Web, how it functioned, and how people could
      create their own websites. This site was the beginning of the World Wide
      Web, and although basic by today's standards, it laid the groundwork for
      the exponential growth that would follow in the years to come.
    </p>
    <p>
      The first website was mainly informational, and its purpose was to help
      others understand the potential of the Web. It served as a guide for
      researchers, academics, and others interested in using this new,
      innovative system to share and access data. Over time, websites would grow
      to become more dynamic, interactive, and visually rich, reflecting the
      incredible potential of the World Wide Web.
    </p>

