    <h2>The Impact</h2>
    <p>
      The introduction of the World Wide Web in the early 1990s quickly gained
      momentum. It turned the internet into a place where people could not only
      access academic and research materials but also share personal ideas,
      businesses, news, and entertainment. The World Wide Web democratized
      access to information, making the internet a powerful tool for
      communication and knowledge-sharing.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Web also played a major role in the rise of e-commerce, social media,
      and search engines-sectors that would become pillars of the modern
      internet economy. The development of web browsers, which made it easy to
      browse websites, and the creation of search engines that indexed this vast
      new source of data, further accelerated the adoption of the Web by the
      general public. Within just a few years, millions of websites sprang up,
      transforming the internet into a global platform for both individuals and
      businesses.
    </p>
    <p>
      The commercialization of the internet followed shortly after the advent of
      the World Wide Web, giving rise to an entirely new global marketplace.
      With websites like Amazon and eBay launching in the mid-1990s, e-commerce
      became a reality, and businesses realized the vast potential of the
      internet for reaching global audiences.
    </p>
